1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:19,210 --> 00:00:19,650
Ozzak!

3
00:00:19,650 --> 00:00:20,090
Ozzak!

4
00:00:26,710 --> 00:00:28,090
Ozzak, what's the meaning of this?

5
00:00:28,110 --> 00:00:29,130
What's all this again?

6
00:00:29,550 --> 00:00:30,950
Uriah Heep released a new album.

7
00:00:31,270 --> 00:00:32,070
Cheers to the dead!

8
00:01:01,450 --> 00:01:02,270
Standard promo.

9
00:01:02,270 --> 00:01:03,230
This is how it's done.

10
00:01:03,850 --> 00:01:05,050
Nobody can miss this.

11
00:01:06,150 --> 00:01:06,950
Look, I've got a granny.

12
00:01:07,250 --> 00:01:08,350
We can test it on her.

13
00:01:12,650 --> 00:01:15,310
See, everyone will think they've walked into a crematorium.

14
00:01:15,310 --> 00:01:19,320
Here we go.

15
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:21,690
Ozzak, what's the meaning of this?

16
00:01:21,950 --> 00:01:26,310
Well, this is another example of how Ozzak interprets the concept of promotion.

17
00:01:26,310 --> 00:01:27,970
I'm surprised you put up with it.

18
00:01:28,950 --> 00:01:32,200
When Citroni last released an album, the health inspectors were here for a week.

19
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:33,280
What's next?

20
00:01:34,750 --> 00:01:38,820
In a month, Euthanasia goes on tour, so I was thinking.

21
00:01:38,820 --> 00:01:39,060
No!

22
00:01:40,050 --> 00:01:41,840
That was a joke, the tour is Slaughterhouse.

23
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:42,320
No!

24
00:01:42,990 --> 00:01:43,670
How about Napalm Death?

25
00:01:43,670 --> 00:01:48,850
No napalm, are you crazy, this is a shop, not a morgue.

26
00:01:48,950 --> 00:01:50,550
You're killing my creativity.

27
00:01:50,770 --> 00:01:53,190
Do you want to turn me into just a selling machine?

28
00:01:53,350 --> 00:01:54,630
And what about that scythe?

29
00:01:54,750 --> 00:01:56,030
If it falls, it'll kill someone.

30
00:01:56,170 --> 00:01:57,530
Bro, I'm no amateur.

31
00:01:57,950 --> 00:02:00,350
I attached it with wire just as solidly as the cross.

32
00:02:03,450 --> 00:02:09,440
When all this junk goes out immediately, it still drives me crazy and scares customers.

33
00:02:09,440 --> 00:02:11,080
And this creature goes first.

34
00:02:11,240 --> 00:02:11,440
What?

35
00:02:12,250 --> 00:02:13,480
Bro, that's our Eddie.

36
00:02:13,480 --> 00:02:13,720
Eddie?

37
00:02:14,750 --> 00:02:18,310
He's been here with us from the start, the laughs we've had together.

38
00:02:18,310 --> 00:02:20,010
Every joke has to end sometime.

39
00:02:23,650 --> 00:02:26,230
Don't worry, Eddie, nothing will happen to you.

40
00:02:26,450 --> 00:02:30,110
You'll just go to a farm with very nice people who love murdering freaks, OK?

41
00:02:30,110 --> 00:02:31,670
Ozzak, you've really lost it.

42
00:02:32,350 --> 00:02:33,650
Take Eddie to recycling.

43
00:02:33,830 --> 00:02:36,070
Recycle him and make toilet paper out of him.

44
00:02:36,290 --> 00:02:37,830
Woman, don't you have a heart at all?

45
00:02:41,650 --> 00:02:44,150
Tomas, come down right away, it's arrived.

46
00:02:46,550 --> 00:02:47,850
Bet you can't guess what I've got.

47
00:02:47,880 --> 00:02:48,740
I couldn't care less.

48
00:02:49,380 --> 00:02:51,640
ABC of Pop, from Adam to Zahorova.

49
00:02:51,780 --> 00:02:53,680
About her I care even less.

50
00:02:54,360 --> 00:02:56,680
Ozzak, this is the bible of popular music.

51
00:02:57,160 --> 00:03:00,400
Wait, presenting, the gospel according to Tomas Pacovsky.

52
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:01,820
Why you and not her?

53
00:03:02,560 --> 00:03:05,580
It's about me, in my own name, Tomas Pacovsky.

54
00:03:05,580 --> 00:03:11,120
After huge interest in the single "You'll Soak Into Me Like Rain," he released two more LPs.

55
00:03:14,550 --> 00:03:15,550
A promising career was cut short by a tragic event.

56
00:03:16,650 --> 00:03:17,750
Oh my God.

57
00:03:18,210 --> 00:03:20,090
It says here that Tomas died.

58
00:03:20,130 --> 00:03:22,210
Excellent, so Eddie can stay.

59
00:03:22,390 --> 00:03:24,570
Stop it, they've just buried him alive.

60
00:03:25,230 --> 00:03:28,310
Ozzak, Tomas must not find out he's dead.

61
00:03:28,390 --> 00:03:29,390
It would kill him.

62
00:03:29,390 --> 00:03:34,870
You called him half a minute ago, so if I'm not mistaken, he'll be here in ten seconds.

63
00:03:34,870 --> 00:03:35,330
Watch.

64
00:03:35,750 --> 00:03:37,650
Ten, nine, eight, seven, four, four and he's here.

65
00:03:40,090 --> 00:03:42,090
So, am I in there or not?

66
00:03:42,850 --> 00:03:45,050
Yes, well actually no.

67
00:03:46,550 --> 00:03:47,650
Yes or no.

68
00:03:47,750 --> 00:03:54,710
Well, the entry, the page with your entry is, I think, missing.

69
00:03:54,710 --> 00:03:55,870
What do you mean?

70
00:03:55,890 --> 00:03:56,690
You didn't look?

71
00:03:56,890 --> 00:03:57,670
I don't think so.

72
00:03:57,830 --> 00:03:58,650
Let's have a look then.

73
00:03:58,750 --> 00:03:59,930
Wait, Tomas, wait.

74
00:03:59,930 --> 00:04:03,970
I also wanted to tell you that Eddie could actually stay.

75
00:04:05,750 --> 00:04:06,310
You think?

76
00:04:07,950 --> 00:04:09,150
Well, if the page is really missing, I think we've gotten used to each other.

77
00:04:14,340 --> 00:04:17,740
If the page really isn't there.

78
00:04:17,860 --> 00:04:18,300
What?

79
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:19,720
Ozzak?

80
00:04:25,150 --> 00:04:26,850
Oh, Ozzak!

81
00:04:26,950 --> 00:04:28,350
Bro, I love you.

82
00:04:30,450 --> 00:04:33,450
Mrs. Marcelka, here's the rest of the books from the car.

83
00:04:36,750 --> 00:04:39,950
Get a case, five beers, and mustard, I can't do this dry.

84
00:04:46,460 --> 00:04:47,640
Hello, Pacovsky speaking.

85
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:49,340
I have a complaint.

86
00:04:49,980 --> 00:04:54,080
You wrote in the ABC of Pop on page 160 that I'm dead.

87
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:56,160
And the problem is that I'm alive.

88
00:04:58,030 --> 00:04:59,390
How dare you, man?

89
00:04:59,390 --> 00:05:01,510
Could you please tell me your name and position?

90
00:05:01,750 --> 00:05:03,150
Yes, I'm Brian, the doorman.

91
00:05:05,050 --> 00:05:07,650
I see, can you connect me to the publishing house?

92
00:05:07,660 --> 00:05:08,060
Thanks.

93
00:05:08,580 --> 00:05:11,580
And how exactly am I supposed to prove I'm alive, young lady?

94
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:12,880
You want to measure my pulse or what?

95
00:05:13,520 --> 00:05:14,780
Fine, it's 180.

96
00:05:15,280 --> 00:05:17,500
And if you don't connect me to the publisher, it'll be 220.

97
00:05:19,490 --> 00:05:20,530
So what should we do?

98
00:05:20,530 --> 00:05:24,450
You'll probably have to pull it from stores and reissue it with a mistake that big, right?

99
00:05:25,440 --> 00:05:26,640
What C, please?

100
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:28,160
I'm P, Pacovsky, right?

101
00:05:29,650 --> 00:05:32,150
Right, category C. So what does that mean?

102
00:05:33,950 --> 00:05:36,350
What, what goodbye?

103
00:05:36,650 --> 00:05:38,830
You haven't heard the last of me!

104
00:05:39,050 --> 00:05:40,450
Hey, dad, what's new?

105
00:05:40,450 --> 00:05:44,650
Well, other than being dead, look, everything is perfectly fine.

106
00:05:45,230 --> 00:05:45,630
At Lake Balaton?

107
00:05:45,750 --> 00:05:45,910
Yeah.

108
00:05:46,030 --> 00:05:47,050
But it's only knee-deep there.

109
00:05:48,750 --> 00:05:49,850
Category C. Gott is an A, Sagvan Tofi is B, and if you're D, you have to pay them to include you at all.

110
00:05:55,050 --> 00:06:00,430
Don't worry, dad, you'll die at ninety-one under a blooming cherry tree, surrounded by grandchildren and Ozzak.

111
00:06:00,430 --> 00:06:03,050
How could they think I'm dead?

112
00:06:03,350 --> 00:06:05,250
They probably saw you in this jacket.

113
00:06:05,880 --> 00:06:09,820
Wait, you put my blazer in the cleaners so I put on this jacket, does it look that terrible?

114
00:06:10,020 --> 00:06:12,560
Dad, people who wore these things died out in '85.

115
00:06:15,650 --> 00:06:18,650
Hey, try calling the papers so they write that you're alive.

116
00:06:18,780 --> 00:06:21,100
Like the tabloids, they'll print any nonsense.

117
00:06:21,620 --> 00:06:22,600
That's an idea.

118
00:06:22,780 --> 00:06:24,040
Well, I'm off.

119
00:06:24,800 --> 00:06:28,080
I need to explain to the class that a raccoon is a disgusting stinky creature.

120
00:06:28,520 --> 00:06:30,720
We're choosing a class mascot and I'm lobbying for the eagle.

121
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:31,680
Bye.

122
00:06:32,650 --> 00:06:40,550
It's about me, since he's alive, it's not news for you, buddy.

123
00:06:40,670 --> 00:06:42,450
Yeah, if I were dead, it would be!

124
00:06:42,570 --> 00:06:46,150
Fine, then please read the Encyclopedia of Pop, page 160.

125
00:06:46,510 --> 00:06:48,070
I'm dead, people!

126
00:06:48,490 --> 00:06:49,010
Dead!

127
00:06:54,350 --> 00:06:56,450
You'll soak into me like rain, and I'll soak into you, you won't find such happiness.

128
00:06:56,750 --> 00:06:57,650
Ozzak!

129
00:06:58,150 --> 00:07:03,520
When I said the wreaths go out of the shop, I didn't mean put them in front of the shop.

130
00:07:03,850 --> 00:07:06,450
But I'm not staying here in a cemetery, OK?

131
00:07:07,670 --> 00:07:09,290
I see he's already gotten into the coffin.

132
00:07:10,150 --> 00:07:11,770
Can you dig a grave?

133
00:07:12,170 --> 00:07:15,070
Ozzak, don't bother Tomas at a time like this.

134
00:07:15,150 --> 00:07:16,550
Besides, he looks good.

135
00:07:16,630 --> 00:07:18,030
Like 20 years ago.

136
00:07:18,830 --> 00:07:22,710
Fine, I'll take off the stupid jacket, there, happy?

137
00:07:22,930 --> 00:07:26,290
And I also thought, Marcelka, that you'd keep an eye on things, that I could count on you.

138
00:07:28,230 --> 00:07:30,050
Why are you playing my songs now?

139
00:07:30,210 --> 00:07:31,990
Do you think that'll win me over?

140
00:07:33,130 --> 00:07:34,190
Sorry, Tomas.

141
00:07:34,850 --> 00:07:37,050
They've been playing you on the radio all morning on repeat.

142
00:07:37,450 --> 00:07:38,450
This is a tragedy.

143
00:07:39,850 --> 00:07:40,890
They're playing me on the radio?

144
00:07:40,890 --> 00:07:41,410
What's going on?

145
00:07:41,950 --> 00:07:45,650
You should hear this from someone close.

146
00:07:47,050 --> 00:07:48,900
Let him hear it from a stranger for all I care.

147
00:07:50,450 --> 00:07:51,050
So that was a hit by Tommy Paci from the eighties.

148
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:56,260
As a tribute to the deceased pop star.

149
00:07:56,640 --> 00:08:00,120
About whom we read today that he managed to drown himself in Lake Balaton.

150
00:08:00,360 --> 00:08:00,880
What!

151
00:08:07,150 --> 00:08:08,550
My sincere condolences.

152
00:08:18,920 --> 00:08:19,560
Good afternoon.

153
00:08:20,100 --> 00:08:20,680
Good afternoon.

154
00:08:21,350 --> 00:08:22,240
I'd like to...

155
00:08:22,250 --> 00:08:24,050
Don't tell me.

156
00:08:24,450 --> 00:08:27,720
You've come to pay tribute to Tommy Paci, right?

157
00:08:28,050 --> 00:08:32,450
Right, so flowers on the ground, plush toys and teddy bears right next to them.

158
00:08:34,950 --> 00:08:36,150
God, what is that supposed to mean?

159
00:08:36,450 --> 00:08:39,630
Excuse me, madam, do you know who I am?

160
00:08:39,630 --> 00:08:40,070
Pardon?

161
00:08:40,170 --> 00:08:40,470
Me.

162
00:08:41,450 --> 00:08:42,650
Oh, the resemblance.

163
00:08:43,550 --> 00:08:45,820
You must be Mr. Pacovsky, right?

164
00:08:46,250 --> 00:08:48,050
I'm Libuska Krobova.

165
00:08:48,180 --> 00:08:49,160
My sincere condolences.

166
00:08:50,130 --> 00:08:52,770
It must be terrible to lose a brother at such a young age.

167
00:08:52,910 --> 00:08:53,930
But I...

168
00:08:53,930 --> 00:08:56,210
I wanted to tell you that I loved him terribly.

169
00:08:56,210 --> 00:08:57,650
I lived only for him.

170
00:08:58,170 --> 00:09:01,210
He was the best singer in the whole world.

171
00:09:01,450 --> 00:09:02,370
Wait, don't cry.

172
00:09:02,490 --> 00:09:03,750
I am Tommy Paci.

173
00:09:03,790 --> 00:09:04,870
Look, Tommy Paci.

174
00:09:04,870 --> 00:09:05,650
I'm alive.

175
00:09:05,650 --> 00:09:06,030
I'm living.

176
00:09:06,230 --> 00:09:07,370
He hasn't even gone cold yet.

177
00:09:07,490 --> 00:09:08,670
And you already want to profit from him?

178
00:09:08,770 --> 00:09:09,210
Disgusting.

179
00:09:09,950 --> 00:09:13,490
That he had to die and not you.

180
00:09:15,150 --> 00:09:15,930
That's enough.

181
00:09:16,390 --> 00:09:18,530
I'm alive, even if it bothers someone.

182
00:09:18,630 --> 00:09:19,750
That will have to be proven.

183
00:09:23,650 --> 00:09:24,910
He left behind a jacket.

184
00:09:25,350 --> 00:09:25,690
That's...

185
00:09:25,950 --> 00:09:26,980
That's the jacket of...

186
00:09:27,750 --> 00:09:28,850
Tommy Paci.

187
00:09:29,150 --> 00:09:30,440
Nobody else's.

188
00:09:30,440 --> 00:09:31,020
I'll buy it.

189
00:09:32,750 --> 00:09:37,950
Damn, you're brave.

190
00:09:37,950 --> 00:09:40,590
Reading in the paper that your dad died and casually going to the zoo.

191
00:09:40,790 --> 00:09:43,370
Who'd miss the zoo over a death in the family?

192
00:09:43,910 --> 00:09:46,640
Especially when dad keeps bugging you in the living room.

193
00:09:47,620 --> 00:09:51,300
I would've enjoyed it a lot more if it weren't for your moronic brother.

194
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:54,920
They had this tiny cage and they were crammed in there.

195
00:09:55,550 --> 00:09:58,560
How would you feel if everyone just spat at you and walked on?

196
00:09:58,560 --> 00:10:00,280
And besides, they're actually quite cute.

197
00:10:02,250 --> 00:10:09,650
Thanks to powerful jaws and effective stomach acids, it can ingest, grind, and digest bones and skin.

198
00:10:09,650 --> 00:10:10,130
Cute.

199
00:10:11,450 --> 00:10:12,550
More like handy.

200
00:10:12,750 --> 00:10:15,150
It's the best class mascot.

201
00:10:15,550 --> 00:10:17,810
Ivo, you're not going to hit him again, are you?

202
00:10:17,810 --> 00:10:20,150
How could you suggest naming it the same as me?

203
00:10:21,010 --> 00:10:22,870
I was surprised too that everyone was for it.

204
00:10:23,150 --> 00:10:25,710
They probably wanted to cheer you up since your dad died.

205
00:10:26,330 --> 00:10:30,890
Maybe it was more because of your speech where you kept explaining that me and hyenas have a lot in common.

206
00:10:31,450 --> 00:10:37,310
I meant to say that you're clever, modest, and can survive even in the harshest conditions.

207
00:10:38,090 --> 00:10:41,910
Good thing nobody took it to mean I have bad breath, spots on my back, and eat corpses.

208
00:10:42,470 --> 00:10:44,770
So that's why it bothered you so much.

209
00:10:47,210 --> 00:10:49,110
But you didn't have to scream about it.

210
00:10:49,310 --> 00:10:50,910
How was I not screaming?

211
00:10:51,350 --> 00:10:52,380
Ivo was screaming.

212
00:10:52,450 --> 00:10:58,040
You were screaming "why did you do it," you were on Lexa's neck, Lexa was crying, and the hyena was licking him through the bars.

213
00:10:58,450 --> 00:11:01,020
I wasn't crying, that was Iva's drool.

214
00:11:01,450 --> 00:11:02,350
Excuse me!

215
00:11:03,350 --> 00:11:05,340
I mean the other Iva, the clever one.

216
00:11:07,350 --> 00:11:13,620
Doctor, I'll be in touch.

217
00:11:13,950 --> 00:11:14,750
Yes, thank you.

218
00:11:15,250 --> 00:11:18,530
Ha, I'll show them, dead they say.

219
00:11:18,550 --> 00:11:20,790
Ivuska, good news.

220
00:11:20,790 --> 00:11:21,630
Daddy will live.

221
00:11:21,970 --> 00:11:22,590
Really?

222
00:11:22,610 --> 00:11:22,850
Really.

223
00:11:23,360 --> 00:11:24,620
I just talked to a lawyer.

224
00:11:24,880 --> 00:11:26,980
Everyone will have to publicly apologize to me.

225
00:11:27,020 --> 00:11:27,480
Everyone.

226
00:11:27,560 --> 00:11:30,460
And if I weren't category C, I could even demand compensation.

227
00:11:30,540 --> 00:11:32,320
I told you it would work out.

228
00:11:36,070 --> 00:11:37,710
Do you have any more jackets?

229
00:11:37,910 --> 00:11:38,410
Jackets?

230
00:11:38,450 --> 00:11:39,750
Jackets, sweaters, anything.

231
00:11:39,810 --> 00:11:40,210
Underwear.

232
00:11:40,470 --> 00:11:41,850
Some of it's dirty.

233
00:11:41,970 --> 00:11:42,450
Excellent.

234
00:11:42,510 --> 00:11:43,590
Dirty is even better.

235
00:11:44,150 --> 00:11:45,470
Good news, Marcelka.

236
00:11:45,570 --> 00:11:46,130
Guess what.

237
00:11:46,750 --> 00:11:47,550
I'm alive.

238
00:11:47,610 --> 00:11:48,170
I can see that.

239
00:11:48,210 --> 00:11:49,090
Ivuska, quick.

240
00:11:49,130 --> 00:11:50,470
It's packed down there.

241
00:11:50,570 --> 00:11:51,910
Ozzak can't hold out much longer.

242
00:11:52,550 --> 00:11:54,410
They could tear our hands off.

243
00:11:54,550 --> 00:11:57,530
People are bringing wreaths and keep wanting to buy stuff from us.

244
00:11:57,950 --> 00:11:59,010
Here's today's takings.

245
00:11:59,010 --> 00:12:02,350
Five thousand more than Ozzak earned in the last ten years.

246
00:12:02,350 --> 00:12:08,290
And this is for your jacket and that old toothbrush I found in the back closet.

247
00:12:08,290 --> 00:12:10,070
Tomas, you're a star.

248
00:12:10,070 --> 00:12:12,910
And wait till I rise from the dead, Marcelka.

249
00:12:12,910 --> 00:12:16,990
If you could stay dead a few more days, we'd make a fortune.

250
00:12:17,450 --> 00:12:20,870
Isn't it immoral to profit from death?

251
00:12:21,580 --> 00:12:23,420
It's your own death.

252
00:12:23,460 --> 00:12:25,040
You can profit from that.

253
00:12:25,440 --> 00:12:26,480
That's true.

254
00:12:26,520 --> 00:12:29,340
I could stay dead for a few days, but only temporarily.

255
00:12:29,600 --> 00:12:31,540
The madness won't last long anyway.

256
00:12:33,750 --> 00:12:36,650
You want to sell those jackets as his estate?

257
00:12:37,150 --> 00:12:39,030
Look how much people value me.

258
00:12:39,450 --> 00:12:41,030
I really didn't think this of you.

259
00:12:41,450 --> 00:12:42,650
What about your honor?

260
00:12:43,050 --> 00:12:46,010
Ivuska, in life you sometimes have to make compromises.

261
00:12:46,150 --> 00:12:47,930
That doesn't seem like a compromise.

262
00:12:48,250 --> 00:12:50,330
You know, you're alive and pretending to be dead.

263
00:12:50,550 --> 00:12:53,950
Yeah, if you pretended to be a zombie, that would be a compromise.

264
00:12:55,970 --> 00:12:56,550
Hi, Ivo.

265
00:12:56,990 --> 00:12:58,250
Those are the black clothes.

266
00:12:58,330 --> 00:13:00,590
Mom wears them to social services when she pretends to be a widow.

267
00:13:00,690 --> 00:13:03,130
You should probably wear them now that your dad is dead.

268
00:13:03,230 --> 00:13:04,330
Good day, Mr. Pacovsky.

269
00:13:05,350 --> 00:13:06,410
You too, Sasha.

270
00:13:17,510 --> 00:13:17,870
Pacovsky?

271
00:13:20,050 --> 00:13:22,550
Wait, wait, orders are always handled by my brother.

272
00:13:22,580 --> 00:13:26,930
Actually, you're right, I've inherited all of this.

273
00:13:27,150 --> 00:13:28,470
I totally forgot about that.

274
00:13:29,270 --> 00:13:29,630
So...

275
00:13:29,630 --> 00:13:30,590
Yeah.

276
00:13:31,220 --> 00:13:31,580
Uh huh.

277
00:13:32,950 --> 00:13:33,930
Yeah, yeah, yeah, I have it here.

278
00:13:33,930 --> 00:13:34,170
And...

279
00:13:34,850 --> 00:13:36,250
Do you only supply records?

280
00:13:38,250 --> 00:13:41,630
Yeah, from pins to locomotives.

281
00:13:41,950 --> 00:13:43,050
Do you have a steamship?

282
00:13:45,350 --> 00:13:48,470
You wouldn't believe how popular they've gotten.

283
00:13:48,750 --> 00:13:51,430
All it took was removing the tags with Tomas's name.

284
00:13:51,650 --> 00:13:56,350
Right, so I'd like to order that special beer from Sweden.

285
00:13:56,850 --> 00:14:00,050
Listen, is it really made from soy beans?

286
00:14:00,210 --> 00:14:01,690
Right, soy beans, I see.

287
00:14:02,050 --> 00:14:03,310
Well, that's fine too.

288
00:14:04,450 --> 00:14:05,450
Twelve then.

289
00:14:06,280 --> 00:14:07,800
Not bottles, cases.

290
00:14:08,440 --> 00:14:09,600
Are you ordering something?

291
00:14:10,610 --> 00:14:11,130
Just a moment.

292
00:14:12,350 --> 00:14:13,650
Marcelka, don't interrupt!

293
00:14:14,250 --> 00:14:17,040
I'm the boss now, we're missing lots of important things here.

294
00:14:17,040 --> 00:14:18,100
So please.

295
00:14:18,100 --> 00:14:21,160
And did you reorder the new Eva Farna CD?

296
00:14:21,160 --> 00:14:21,680
One moment.

297
00:14:22,650 --> 00:14:24,180
I said important things.

298
00:14:24,180 --> 00:14:27,140
Ozzak, yesterday we sold all ten we had.

299
00:14:27,200 --> 00:14:28,340
That's important.

300
00:14:28,500 --> 00:14:28,940
It's not.

301
00:14:28,940 --> 00:14:30,340
What we had to sell, we sold.

302
00:14:30,420 --> 00:14:30,820
End of story.

303
00:14:30,980 --> 00:14:33,800
Leave me alone, I still need to order some things.

304
00:14:33,880 --> 00:14:34,060
Hello?

305
00:14:35,050 --> 00:14:40,350
Hey, I'd really love that silver thing you have on page 116.

306
00:14:46,150 --> 00:14:46,950
Come, Tomas.

307
00:14:47,610 --> 00:14:48,050
Bro!

308
00:14:52,050 --> 00:14:55,950
Tomas, I brought you some sweets since you were here all alone.

309
00:14:56,550 --> 00:14:57,650
A cream puff and a coffin cake, huh?

310
00:15:00,050 --> 00:15:01,650
Come, come, come.

311
00:15:02,150 --> 00:15:03,650
Bro, what's it like being dead?

312
00:15:04,450 --> 00:15:06,100
I had a wonderful rest.

313
00:15:07,550 --> 00:15:10,050
I'm telling you, everyone should try it once in a while.

314
00:15:12,550 --> 00:15:14,150
Here's today's takings.

315
00:15:14,650 --> 00:15:17,050
I don't know if it's worth it.

316
00:15:17,750 --> 00:15:21,440
You've been locked up here all day, you're pale as death.

317
00:15:21,440 --> 00:15:22,500
Death, shmeath.

318
00:15:22,500 --> 00:15:24,680
What matters is that business is booming.

319
00:15:24,950 --> 00:15:27,080
Dad will come see for himself tomorrow then.

320
00:15:27,080 --> 00:15:27,580
Right?

321
00:15:27,980 --> 00:15:31,300
I think maybe tomorrow isn't quite the right time yet.

322
00:15:31,460 --> 00:15:32,920
Have you completely lost your mind?

323
00:15:33,140 --> 00:15:35,340
Dad's not going to be locked up like in some prison.

324
00:15:35,660 --> 00:15:36,180
Ivuska.

325
00:15:36,450 --> 00:15:39,650
I know money isn't everything, but a little sacrifice is worth it.

326
00:15:39,790 --> 00:15:40,610
See, Tomas?

327
00:15:40,870 --> 00:15:43,010
No, no, Marcelka, I said one day.

328
00:15:43,330 --> 00:15:44,930
But think of the people.

329
00:15:44,950 --> 00:15:47,510
You wouldn't want to spoil their joy, I mean grief.

330
00:15:47,750 --> 00:15:49,330
And it's also about your family.

331
00:15:49,570 --> 00:15:51,610
You shouldn't decide something like this alone.

332
00:15:51,670 --> 00:15:55,290
There should be a vote on whether Tomas should stay dead or not.

333
00:15:55,730 --> 00:15:59,950
Marcelka, my family would never stoop to such hyena-like profiteering.

334
00:16:00,110 --> 00:16:00,870
Well, great.

335
00:16:00,910 --> 00:16:02,990
I'm for it and I'm only doing it for your own good.

336
00:16:03,090 --> 00:16:04,910
Well great, I'm firmly against.

337
00:16:05,030 --> 00:16:05,510
Me too.

338
00:16:06,150 --> 00:16:06,710
Still Ozzak.

339
00:16:06,850 --> 00:16:07,550
Ozzak.

340
00:16:08,790 --> 00:16:09,310
Ozzak.

341
00:16:09,310 --> 00:16:12,950
We're voting on whether Tomas should stay dead or not.

342
00:16:13,210 --> 00:16:14,450
I'm definitely for it.

343
00:16:14,450 --> 00:16:18,330
The shop is still missing a ton of important stuff.

344
00:16:18,330 --> 00:16:19,150
So it's a tie.

345
00:16:19,850 --> 00:16:20,550
Two-two.

346
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:23,140
Hold on.

347
00:16:24,550 --> 00:16:26,750
How come he gets to vote when he's dead?

348
00:16:28,360 --> 00:16:28,880
Hi.

349
00:16:28,880 --> 00:16:29,150
You must be Iva.

350
00:16:30,140 --> 00:16:31,000
I'm Lukas Jaros.

351
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:35,650
From social services, I'm here to help you cope with your father's death.

352
00:16:37,150 --> 00:16:40,750
Wow, I didn't know social workers were this handsome.

353
00:16:40,750 --> 00:16:41,610
I mean young.

354
00:16:41,950 --> 00:16:44,030
I'm here to help you.

355
00:16:44,550 --> 00:16:45,450
Is this your family?

356
00:16:45,750 --> 00:16:46,970
Well, basically.

357
00:16:46,970 --> 00:16:49,730
Uncle, second uncle, non-biological aunt.

358
00:16:50,150 --> 00:16:52,350
But how would you help me?

359
00:16:53,650 --> 00:17:00,550
Well, I think for a start, it would be enough if we started meeting more often.

360
00:17:00,910 --> 00:17:01,650
Really?

361
00:17:01,650 --> 00:17:03,950
Even in the evening?

362
00:17:04,050 --> 00:17:05,950
If that works for you, why not?

363
00:17:05,950 --> 00:17:10,250
Because evenings are the worst, the loneliness, the sadness and all.

364
00:17:11,150 --> 00:17:13,850
Go have a nice cry, it helps, and we'll see each other tonight.

365
00:17:14,910 --> 00:17:15,450
Thank you.

366
00:17:15,850 --> 00:17:16,550
Hang in there.

367
00:17:21,850 --> 00:17:24,050
I demand a new vote.

368
00:17:47,530 --> 00:17:48,070
Simona.

369
00:17:48,230 --> 00:17:48,470
Tome.

370
00:17:49,650 --> 00:17:52,950
How many times have I asked you not to use that lock pick.

371
00:17:53,150 --> 00:17:56,350
Sorry, if I'd known you were home, I would've just rung the bell.

372
00:17:56,420 --> 00:17:57,200
I ran out of coffee.

373
00:17:57,460 --> 00:17:59,200
Hey, want to have that coffee here with me?

374
00:17:59,500 --> 00:17:59,960
I'd love to.

375
00:18:09,380 --> 00:18:12,890
That could wake the dead.

376
00:18:12,890 --> 00:18:16,250
So I don't know, won't you sit down so we can chat?

377
00:18:16,950 --> 00:18:18,450
I can't, I have a shift.

378
00:18:19,350 --> 00:18:21,230
Big changes at the Badger now.

379
00:18:21,230 --> 00:18:25,650
Hey Tome, do you have any photos from when we took the kids on vacation to Machac?

380
00:18:25,850 --> 00:18:28,350
Of course I do.

381
00:18:28,950 --> 00:18:29,550
Here, there's more in the big album on page 15.

382
00:18:32,750 --> 00:18:34,670
I've gone through everything five times.

383
00:18:35,100 --> 00:18:36,700
Being dead is incredibly boring.

384
00:18:36,780 --> 00:18:37,240
Show me.

385
00:18:40,850 --> 00:18:42,450
At Machac, are there dead fish?

386
00:18:42,850 --> 00:18:44,750
That's when bees stung Lexa.

387
00:18:45,650 --> 00:18:48,990
Who can remember all these beautiful memories?

388
00:18:49,050 --> 00:18:51,310
This one's good though, it looks like it's from Balaton.

389
00:18:51,310 --> 00:18:52,050
Can I borrow it?

390
00:18:52,390 --> 00:18:52,870
Thanks.

391
00:18:53,550 --> 00:18:54,450
Gotta run, bye.

392
00:18:54,690 --> 00:18:57,770
Hey, wouldn't you want to maybe stop by tonight so we can chat?

393
00:18:58,010 --> 00:18:59,430
Or even at night?

394
00:18:59,430 --> 00:19:00,230
Or tomorrow?

395
00:19:02,550 --> 00:19:03,550
Day after tomorrow.

396
00:19:07,790 --> 00:19:09,570
Don't worry, I'm fine.

397
00:19:09,570 --> 00:19:15,350
I might seem a bit irritable, but that's because of everything happening around me.

398
00:19:16,150 --> 00:19:19,450
But being home alone all day is really no fun.

399
00:19:20,250 --> 00:19:25,450
Luckily we can chat quietly like this, but if I were alone here, I'd go crazy, trust me.

400
00:19:25,950 --> 00:19:26,850
Like this.

401
00:19:26,950 --> 00:19:27,650
Yeah.

402
00:19:31,450 --> 00:19:33,900
You're laughing now, but wait till winter.

403
00:19:34,750 --> 00:19:44,550
Ivuska, finally, we have so much to discuss.

404
00:19:44,570 --> 00:19:47,330
Dad, I really don't have time, but we'll talk the day after tomorrow, OK?

405
00:19:47,430 --> 00:19:47,710
Yeah.

406
00:19:47,810 --> 00:19:50,050
But do you think they could be shortened somehow?

407
00:19:50,250 --> 00:19:51,890
I don't think that'll be necessary.

408
00:19:51,910 --> 00:19:52,830
We just need to pin it.

409
00:19:52,830 --> 00:19:53,430
Got pins?

410
00:19:53,610 --> 00:19:53,850
Yeah.

411
00:19:55,750 --> 00:19:59,120
Mr. Pacovsky, I really want to ask you something, but I'm a bit embarrassed.

412
00:19:59,120 --> 00:20:00,420
Go ahead, ask away, girl.

413
00:20:01,250 --> 00:20:02,640
Is there something after death?

414
00:20:02,640 --> 00:20:04,160
Like another life?

415
00:20:04,340 --> 00:20:05,620
You would know.

416
00:20:05,900 --> 00:20:09,040
Well, after death it's mainly really boring.

417
00:20:09,500 --> 00:20:10,260
Here they are.

418
00:20:10,320 --> 00:20:10,800
Give me those.

419
00:20:13,450 --> 00:20:17,040
Hey, how do you think I should act around him since he's a social worker?

420
00:20:17,350 --> 00:20:21,380
Mom always says I should cry a lot and Lexa should act like an idiot.

421
00:20:21,380 --> 00:20:23,380
That shouldn't be a problem for him, right?

422
00:20:24,150 --> 00:20:28,350
I should probably reminisce a lot so he starts comforting me, right?

423
00:20:28,480 --> 00:20:32,040
Yeah, you should reminisce, something touching, about childhood and stuff.

424
00:20:32,040 --> 00:20:37,790
I could tell him how dad used to tuck me in and brought me milk and a cookie and...

425
00:20:37,850 --> 00:20:39,550
And took me on trips.

426
00:20:39,590 --> 00:20:43,090
Dad only took us on a trip once, then I never saw him again.

427
00:20:43,310 --> 00:20:43,730
How come?

428
00:20:44,030 --> 00:20:46,610
We were driving really fast and something kept honking.

429
00:20:46,710 --> 00:20:50,910
Then we ran through the forest Indian-style and I think there was a hunt because they kept shooting.

430
00:20:51,050 --> 00:20:54,410
Then dad hid us in a haystack and said he'd come back for us.

431
00:20:54,510 --> 00:20:55,390
And did he?

432
00:20:55,970 --> 00:21:00,050
Lexa and I spent some time in foster care until mom picked us up under a window one night.

433
00:21:00,790 --> 00:21:04,290
Well, back then I was driving Simona somewhere and...

434
00:21:09,250 --> 00:21:15,950
And what happened was it rained terribly and we got soaked to the bone.

435
00:21:28,250 --> 00:21:33,250
Who would've thought you could trip out this much on those beans.

436
00:21:34,050 --> 00:21:37,150
Ozzak, would you have a comb?

437
00:21:37,750 --> 00:21:40,020
I'd need something small over here on the right.

438
00:21:40,350 --> 00:21:41,450
Yeah, back there.

439
00:21:42,180 --> 00:21:42,860
Yeah.

440
00:21:42,860 --> 00:21:43,650
Where are you going?

441
00:21:46,550 --> 00:21:47,550
In the back.

442
00:21:56,050 --> 00:22:01,570
I'll tell you, it's only after something happens that you realize how little you knew him.

443
00:22:02,250 --> 00:22:04,530
They're just fragments.

444
00:22:05,050 --> 00:22:09,250
How he loved to laugh, that he enjoyed good food.

445
00:22:10,050 --> 00:22:13,550
We never even got a chance to properly talk.

446
00:22:15,400 --> 00:22:16,100
Talk?

447
00:22:16,850 --> 00:22:19,850
I feel like I'm a ghost.

448
00:22:21,420 --> 00:22:23,260
I miss a warm human word.

449
00:22:23,520 --> 00:22:24,820
Like a sausage, for example.

450
00:22:28,950 --> 00:22:31,550
The last supper of Tomas Pacovsky.

451
00:22:32,460 --> 00:22:33,900
This has to end.

452
00:22:33,900 --> 00:22:38,100
I'll carry out my resurrection right now.

453
00:22:38,650 --> 00:22:44,220
We know you feel cramped in that apartment, like...

454
00:22:44,220 --> 00:22:46,860
Like a drowned man in a coffin, you know, bro?

455
00:22:46,980 --> 00:22:49,080
But you only have to hold out until today.

456
00:22:49,180 --> 00:22:50,040
And you know what?

457
00:22:50,220 --> 00:22:53,080
With that thing on your head, you're barely recognizable.

458
00:22:53,080 --> 00:22:53,400
No?

459
00:22:53,400 --> 00:22:53,540
No.

460
00:22:54,160 --> 00:22:57,020
Disguise yourself a bit more and feel free to go outside for some air.

461
00:22:57,140 --> 00:23:01,060
At least then I can bring the senior tour group upstairs and show them the bedroom.

462
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:02,420
Yeah, you look terribly pale.

463
00:23:03,350 --> 00:23:07,050
Come on, half-dead, go, go get some fresh air, go, go.

464
00:23:19,410 --> 00:23:20,450
What'll you have?

465
00:23:20,450 --> 00:23:24,950
Paci's lager, want Pilsner Glory or Pacifola?

466
00:23:25,450 --> 00:23:29,210
Yes, you're in the bar frequented by the famous and dead Tommy Paci.

467
00:23:29,550 --> 00:23:33,410
Tommy and I were very close, my son looks a lot like him.

468
00:23:34,650 --> 00:23:35,810
Simona, what's the meaning of this?

469
00:23:35,810 --> 00:23:36,430
What?

470
00:23:37,050 --> 00:23:38,350
I'm just making money.

471
00:23:38,450 --> 00:23:40,670
Advertising like crazy, didn't cost me a thing.

472
00:23:40,670 --> 00:23:41,850
You can't be serious?

473
00:23:42,450 --> 00:23:43,950
You know how many people come here now?

474
00:23:44,010 --> 00:23:45,230
Like this woman.

475
00:23:45,330 --> 00:23:46,330
She's here every day.

476
00:23:46,750 --> 00:23:47,950
And she even cleans for me.

477
00:23:49,150 --> 00:23:53,960
This place used to be such a dump and now it's nice.

478
00:23:53,960 --> 00:23:55,360
Libuska, good day.

479
00:23:57,050 --> 00:23:58,050
It's you.

480
00:23:58,420 --> 00:23:58,940
You hyena.

481
00:23:59,550 --> 00:24:00,950
Oh no!

482
00:24:01,350 --> 00:24:04,720
I'm Tommy Paci, I'm not dead, I'm alive.

483
00:24:04,720 --> 00:24:05,840
How dare you?

484
00:24:06,600 --> 00:24:07,280
Like this.

485
00:24:07,850 --> 00:24:15,650
Wait, calm down, look, wait, ID card, I'm Tommy Paci, read it, read it.

486
00:24:17,050 --> 00:24:17,850
See, that's me.

487
00:24:18,760 --> 00:24:19,500
For you.

488
00:24:36,070 --> 00:24:38,090
I'm fascinated by how quickly you got through it.

489
00:24:38,230 --> 00:24:39,230
But that's mainly thanks to you.

490
00:24:39,370 --> 00:24:42,590
Some people take months, but you managed the whole thing in two days.

491
00:24:42,630 --> 00:24:44,970
It's clear you can handle your father's death on your own now.

492
00:24:45,740 --> 00:24:46,200
On my own?

493
00:24:48,550 --> 00:24:49,850
My dad is dead?

494
00:24:49,950 --> 00:24:50,750
Oh damn.

495
00:24:51,650 --> 00:24:53,450
We're back to denial.

496
00:24:53,950 --> 00:24:55,050
This has never happened to me.

497
00:24:55,450 --> 00:24:57,550
I could tell this wasn't going to be a simple case.

498
00:24:58,550 --> 00:24:59,350
So could I.

499
00:24:59,450 --> 00:25:02,350
What is this paw doing here?

500
00:25:03,250 --> 00:25:04,350
And who are you?

501
00:25:04,950 --> 00:25:05,850
Her father.

502
00:25:06,450 --> 00:25:07,050
And alive.

503
00:25:07,280 --> 00:25:07,740
Alive!

504
00:25:09,250 --> 00:25:11,350
Ivo, what is this supposed to mean?

505
00:25:11,670 --> 00:25:12,190
Daddy?

506
00:25:17,550 --> 00:25:19,750
Where have you been, Tomas?

507
00:25:23,960 --> 00:25:25,420
Bro, you'll put us in the grave.

508
00:25:25,720 --> 00:25:27,420
I brought you to a grave.

509
00:25:27,480 --> 00:25:29,980
Look at what your circus is doing to people.

510
00:25:30,140 --> 00:25:30,720
People, huh?

511
00:25:31,220 --> 00:25:32,620
Iva is being comforted by someone.

512
00:25:32,820 --> 00:25:35,000
Simona, whose bar is packed, has never been happier.

513
00:25:35,260 --> 00:25:36,820
Tomas, think of the business.

514
00:25:37,720 --> 00:25:40,480
So I'm supposed to choose between money and life?

515
00:25:40,720 --> 00:25:42,620
You want me to be dead?

516
00:25:42,740 --> 00:25:43,220
Well?

517
00:25:43,750 --> 00:25:45,100
Tomas, keep it down.

518
00:25:45,350 --> 00:25:46,450
We're alone here.

519
00:25:58,150 --> 00:26:00,100
Tomas, have you heard?

520
00:26:00,100 --> 00:26:01,720
You're in the papers again.

521
00:26:01,840 --> 00:26:04,800
And they're writing very nice things about me.

522
00:26:04,860 --> 00:26:07,200
I wouldn't be surprised if people wanted to lynch me now.

523
00:26:07,340 --> 00:26:07,900
Easy, bro.

524
00:26:08,500 --> 00:26:10,600
From what I hear, nothing is decided yet.

525
00:26:11,120 --> 00:26:12,060
Definitely not.

526
00:26:26,550 --> 00:26:26,970
Really everything?

527
00:26:27,250 --> 00:26:28,450
